<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">After enough 12-hour shifts, your feet and back will make this decision for you. Here's what actually holds up — from someone who's been wearing nursing shoes on hard hospital floors for years.</p>

<div class="hero-note">
<strong>Quick picks:</strong> Best overall → <strong>Hoka Bondi 8</strong>. Best clog → <strong>Dansko Professional</strong>. Best for wide feet → <strong>New Balance 990v6</strong>. Best budget → <strong>Crocs On-The-Clock Clog</strong>.
</div>

<h2>Why Nursing Shoe Choice Actually Matters</h2>
<p>Nurses walk 4–5 miles per shift on average. ICU nurses often walk less distance but stand for longer periods and move between patient rooms constantly. ED nurses log more steps. Either way, you're on your feet for 12+ hours on hard vinyl or concrete floors, often without more than a 20-minute break.</p>
<p>Bad footwear over a nursing career contributes to plantar fasciitis, knee problems, hip problems, and lumbar spine issues. This is not a minor quality-of-life issue — it's a career longevity issue. A $150 pair of shoes that protects your joints is one of the highest-ROI purchases a nurse can make.</p>

